&amp;#x2009;<Math>=</Math>&amp;#x2009;0.366), hospitalization (p&amp;#x2009;<Math>=</Math>&amp;#x2009;0.121), life-threatening events (p&amp;#x2009;<Math>=</Math>&amp;#x2009;0.089), or other serious events (p&amp;#x2009;<Math>=</Math>&amp;#x2009;0.169).[para10417_35369572103]</ParaInd><br/><sec3/><title3><label><bold>3.4.2</bold></label><bold> Gender differences</bold>.[para10418_35369572103]</title3><br/><ParaFlushLeft>Male patients had a significantly higher mortality rate than females (5/23 vs. 1/48, p&amp;#x2009;<Math>=</Math>&amp;#x2009;0.012). Both genders most commonly experienced &amp;#x201C;Hospitalization&amp;#x201D; and &amp;#x201C;Other serious medical events,&amp;#x201D; with no significant differences in disability or life-threatening events. For detailed outcomes, refer to <FigureCitation><FigXref>Figures</FigXref><FigXref> </FigXref><FigXref>5D</FigXref></FigureCitation>, <FigureCitation><FigXref>5E</FigXref></FigureCitation>, and [Subxref6]<SupplMaterialCitation><SupplementaryMaterialXref>S6</SupplementaryMaterialXref></SupplMaterialCitation>-7 Table.[para10419_35369572103]</ParaFlushLeft><br/><sec2/><title2><label><bold>3.5</bold></label><bold> Risk factors associated </bold><boldHLC><bold>with</bold></boldHLC><bold> </bold><bold>IC</bold><bold> occurrence</bold>[para10420_35369572103]</title2><br/><ParaFlushLeft>Univariate and multivariate logistic analyses revealed that <allcaps>IC</allcaps> was significantly associated with age and body weight but not with gender (<TableCitation><TabXref>Table</TabXref><TabXref> </TabXref><TabXref>6</TabXref></TableCitation>).[para10421_35369572103]</ParaFlushLeft><br/><TableCaption><tablenumber><bold>Table</bold></tablenumber><tablenumber><bold> </bold></tablenumber><tablenumber><bold>6</bold></tablenumber><tablenumber><bold>.</bold></tablenumber><bold> Logistic regression analysis of </bold><bold>ischemic</bold><bold> colitis</bold><bold> occurrence.</bold>[para10422_35369572103]</TableCaption><br/><p><table f